# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ovhcloud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] A **colocation centre** (also spelled **co-location**, or shortened to **colo**) or "**carrier hotel**", is a type of data centre where equipment, space, and bandwidth are available for rental to retail customers.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Colocation facilities provide space, power, cooling, and physical security for the server, storage, and networking equipment of other firms and also connect them to a variety of telecommunications and network service providers with a minimum of cost and complexity.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] The term "carrier hotel" can refer to a data centre focused on connecting customer and carrier networks together.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Many colocation providers sell to a wide range of customers, ranging from large enterprises to small companies.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Typically, the customer owns the information technology (IT) equipment and the facility provides power and cooling.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Customers retain control over the design and usage of their equipment, but daily management of the data centre and facility are overseen by the multi-tenant colocation provider.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] They may also have a network operations centre (NOC), a help desk, and offices for customer employees, and they may offer remote hands or smart hands service in which on site technicians employed by the colocation provider are allowed to access customer equipment on request to solve customer issues.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Some providers also provide roof access to customers for mounting wireless equipment.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Buildings with data centres inside them are often easy to recognise by the amount of cooling equipment located outside or on the roof.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Colocation data centres are often audited to prove that they attain certain standards and levels of reliability; the most commonly seen systems are SSAE 16 SOC 1 Type I and Type II (formerly SAS 70 Type I and Type II) and the tier system by the Uptime Institute or TIA.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] For service organisations today, SSAE 16 calls for a description of its "system".
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] This is far more detailed and comprehensive than SAS 70's description of "controls".
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Other data centre compliance standards include Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) audit and PCI DSS Standards.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Colocation facilities generally have generators that start automatically when utility power fails, usually running on diesel fuel.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] These generators may have varying levels of redundancy, depending on how the facility is built.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Generators do not start instantaneously, so colocation facilities usually have battery backup systems.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] In many facilities, the operator of the facility provides large inverters to provide AC power from the batteries.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] In other cases, customers may install smaller UPSes in their racks.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Some customers choose to use equipment that is powered directly by 48 VDC (nominal) battery banks.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] This may provide better energy efficiency, and may reduce the number of parts that can fail, though the reduced voltage greatly increases necessary current, and thus the size (and cost) of power delivery wiring.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] An alternative to batteries is a motor–generator connected to a flywheel and diesel engine.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Many colocation facilities can provide redundant, A and B power feeds to customer equipment, and high end servers and telecommunications equipment often can have two power supplies installed.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Colocation facilities are sometimes connected to multiple sections of the utility power grid for additional reliability.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Colocation facility owners have differing rules regarding cross-connects between their customers, some of whom may be carriers.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] These rules may allow customers to run such connections at no charge, or allow customers to order such connections for a monthly fee.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] They may allow customers to order cross-connects to carriers, but not to other customers.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Some colocation centres feature a "meet-me-room" where the different carriers housed in the centre can efficiently exchange data.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] Most peering points sit in colocation centres and because of the high concentration of servers inside larger colocation centres, most carriers will be interested in bringing direct connections to such buildings.
[src:ovhcloud/colocation-centre] In many cases, there will be a larger Internet exchange point hosted inside a colocation centre, where customers can connect for peering.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] A **dedicated hosting service**, **dedicated server**, or **managed hosting service** is a type of Internet hosting in which the client leases an entire server not shared with anyone else.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] This is more flexible than shared hosting, as organizations have full control over the server(s), including choice of operating system, hardware, etc.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] There is also another level of dedicated or managed hosting commonly referred to as complex managed hosting.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Complex managed hosting applies to both physical dedicated servers, hybrid server and virtual servers, with many companies choosing a hybrid (combination of physical and virtual) hosting solution.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] There are many similarities between standard and complex managed hosting but the key difference is the level of administrative and engineering support that the customer pays for – owing to both the increased size and complexity of the infrastructure deployment.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] The provider steps in to take over most of the management, including security, memory, storage and IT support.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] The service is primarily proactive in nature.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Server administration can usually be provided by the hosting company as an add-on service.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] In some cases a dedicated server can offer less overhead and a larger return on investment.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Dedicated servers are hosted in data centers, often providing redundant power sources and HVAC systems.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] In contrast to colocation, the server hardware is owned by the provider and in some cases they will provide support for operating systems or applications.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Using a dedicated hosting service offers the benefits of high performance, security, email stability, and control.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Due to the relatively high price of dedicated hosting, it is mostly used by websites that receive a large volume of traffic.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Availability, price and employee familiarity often determines which operating systems are offered on dedicated servers.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Variations of Linux and Unix (open source operating systems) are often included at no charge to the customer.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Commercial operating systems include Microsoft Windows Server, provided through a special program called Microsoft Services Provider License Agreement, or SPLA.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Red Hat Enterprise is a commercial version of Linux offered to hosting providers on a monthly fee basis.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] The monthly fee provides OS updates through the Red Hat Network using an application called Yum.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Other operating systems are available from the open source community at no charge.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] These include CentOS, Fedora Core, Debian, and many other Linux distributions or BSD systems FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Support for any of these operating systems typically depends on the level of management offered with a particular dedicated server plan.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Operating system support may include updates to the core system in order to acquire the latest security fixes, patches, and system-wide vulnerability resolutions.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Updates to core operating systems include kernel upgrades, service packs, application updates, and security patches that keep the server secure and safe.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Operating system updates and support relieves the burden of server management from the dedicated server owner.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Bandwidth refers to the data transfer rate or the amount of data that can be carried from one point to another in a given time period (usually a second) and is often represented in bits (of data) per second (bit/s).
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Line speed, billed on the 95th percentile, refers to the speed in which data flows from the server or device, measured every five minutes for the month, and dropping the top 5% of measurements that are highest, and basing the usage for the month on the next-highest measurement.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] This is similar to a median measurement, which can be thought of as a 50th percentile measurement (with 50% of measurements above, and 50% of measurements below), whereas this sets the cutoff at 95th percentile, with 5% of measurements above the value, and 95% of measurements below the value.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] This is also known as Burstable billing.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Line speed is measured in bits per second (or kilobits per second, megabits per second or gigabits per second).
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] The second bandwidth measurement is unmetered service where providers cap or control the "top line" speed for a server.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Top line speed in unmetered bandwidth is the total Mbit/s allocated to the server and configured on the switch level.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Unmetered bandwidth services usually incur an additional charge.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] The term “unmetered” is often confused with “unlimited” especially when comparing seedbox service plans.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Some providers will calculate the Total Transfer, which is the measurement of actual data leaving and arriving, measured in bytes.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Although it is typically the sum of all traffic into and out of the server, some providers measure only outbound traffic (traffic from the server to the internet).
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] One of the reasons for choosing to outsource dedicated servers is the availability of high powered networks from multiple providers.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] As dedicated server providers utilize massive amounts of bandwidth, they are able to secure lower volume based pricing to include a multi-provider blend of bandwidth.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] To achieve the same type of network without a multi-provider blend of bandwidth, a large investment in core routers, long term contracts, and expensive monthly bills would need to be in place.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] The expenses needed to develop a network without a multi-provider blend of bandwidth does not make sense economically for hosting providers.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Many dedicated server providers include a service level agreement based on network up-time.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Some dedicated server hosting providers offer a 100% up-time guarantee on their network.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] By securing multiple vendors for connectivity and using redundant hardware, providers are able to guarantee higher up-times; usually between 99 and 100% up-time if they are a higher quality provider.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] One aspect of higher quality providers is they are most likely to be multi-homed across multiple quality up-link providers, which in turn, provides significant redundancy in the event one goes down in addition to potentially improved routes to destinations.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Bandwidth consumption over the last several years has shifted from a per megabit usage model to a per gigabyte usage model.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Bandwidth was traditionally measured inline speed access that included the ability to purchase needed megabits at a given monthly cost.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] As the shared hosting model developed, the trend towards gigabyte or total bytes transferred, replaced the megabit line speed model so dedicated server providers started offering per gigabyte.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Dedicated hosting services primarily differ from managed hosting services in that managed hosting services usually offer more support and other services.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] As such, managed hosting is targeted towards clients with less technical knowledge, whereas dedicated hosting services, or unmanaged hosting services, are suitable for web development and system administrator professionals.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] To date, no industry standards have been set to clearly define the management role of dedicated server providers.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] What this means is that each provider will use industry standard terms, but each provider will define them differently.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] For some dedicated server providers, fully managed is defined as having a web based control panel while other providers define it as having dedicated system engineers readily available to handle all server and network related functions of the dedicated server provider.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Dedicated hosting server providers define their level of management based on the services they provide.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] In comparison, fully managed could equal self managed from provider to provider.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Administrative maintenance of the operating system, often including upgrades, security patches, and sometimes even daemon updates are included.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Differing levels of management may include adding users, domains, daemon configuration, or even custom programming.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Dedicated hosting server providers utilize extreme security measures to ensure the safety of data stored on their network of servers.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Providers will often deploy various software programs for scanning systems and networks for obtrusive invaders, spammers, hackers, and other harmful problems such as Trojans, worms, and crashers (Sending multiple connections).
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Linux and Windows use different software for security protection.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Providers often bill for dedicated servers on a fixed monthly price to include specific software packages.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Over the years, software vendors realized the significant market opportunity to bundle their software with dedicated servers.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] They have since started introducing pricing models that allow dedicated hosting providers the ability to purchase and resell software based on reduced monthly fees.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Microsoft offers software licenses through a program called the Service Provider License Agreement.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] The SPLA model provides use of Microsoft products through a monthly user or processor based fee.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] SPLA software includes the Windows Operating System, Microsoft SQL Server, Microsoft Exchange Server, Microsoft SharePoint and shoutcast hosting, and many other server based products.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Other software applications available are specialized web hosting specific programs called control panels.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Control panel software is an all-inclusive set of software applications, server applications, and automation tools that can be installed on a dedicated server.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Control panels include integration into web servers, database applications, programming languages, application deployment, server administration tasks, and include the ability to automate tasks via a web based front end.
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] Many providers do not allow IRC (bots, clients or daemons).
[src:ovhcloud/dedicated-hosting-service] This is due to rogue IRC users triggering DDoS attacks against the provider, which may overwhelm their networks, lowering service quality for all customers.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] An **Internet service provider** (**ISP**) is an organization that provides a myriad of services related to accessing, using, managing, or participating in the Internet.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] ISPs can be organized in various forms, such as commercial, community-owned, non-profit, or otherwise privately owned.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Internet services typically provided by ISPs can include Internet access, Internet transit, domain name registration, web hosting, and colocation.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] The Internet (originally ARPAnet) was developed as a network between government research laboratories and participating departments of universities.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Other companies and organizations joined by direct connection to the backbone, or by arrangements through other connected companies, sometimes using dialup tools such as UUCP.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] By the late 1980s, a process was set in place towards public, commercial use of the Internet.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Some restrictions were removed by 1991, shortly after the introduction of the World Wide Web.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] During the 1980s, online service providers such as CompuServe, Prodigy, and America Online (AOL) began to offer limited capabilities to access the Internet, such as e-mail interchange, but full access to the Internet was not readily available to the general public.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] In 1989, the first Internet service providers, companies offering the public direct access to the Internet for a monthly fee, were established in Australia and the United States.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] In Brookline, Massachusetts, The World became the first commercial ISP in the US.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Its first customer was served in November 1989.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] These companies generally offered dial-up connections, using the public telephone network to provide last-mile connections to their customers.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] The barriers to entry for dial-up ISPs were low and many providers emerged.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] However, cable television companies and the telephone carriers already had wired connections to their customers and could offer Internet connections at much higher speeds than dial-up using broadband technology such as cable modems and digital subscriber line (DSL).
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] As a result, these companies often became the dominant ISPs in their service areas, and what was once a highly competitive ISP market became effectively a monopoly or duopoly in countries with a commercial telecommunications market, such as the United States.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] In 1995, NSFNET was decommissioned removing the last restrictions on the use of the Internet to carry commercial traffic and network access points were created to allow peering arrangements between commercial ISPs.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] ISPs can be lucrative targets for cybercrime, specifically for data breach exploitation where combinations of email addresses and passwords can be stolen.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] In 2026, six ISPs in Japan were hacked, impacting up to 14,000,000 customers; neither the criminal entity nor the ultimate impact of this breath have yet been determined.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Federal Communications Commission (FCC) was reported to be considering a new rule permitting ISPs to offer content providers a faster track to send content, thus reversing their earlier net neutrality position.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] A possible solution to net neutrality concerns may be municipal broadband, according to Professor Susan Crawford, a legal and technology expert at Harvard Law School.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] On 15 May 2014, the FCC decided to consider two options regarding Internet services: first, permit fast and slow broadband lanes, thereby compromising net neutrality; and second, reclassify broadband as a telecommunications service, thereby preserving net neutrality.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] On 10 November 2014, President Barack Obama recommended that the FCC reclassify broadband Internet service as a telecommunications service in order to preserve net neutrality.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] On 16 January 2015, Republicans presented legislation, in the form of a U.S.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Congress H.R. discussion draft bill, that makes concessions to net neutrality but prohibits the FCC from accomplishing the goal or enacting any further regulation affecting Internet service providers.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] On 31 January 2015, AP News reported that the FCC will present the notion of applying ("with some caveats") Title II (common carrier) of the Communications Act of 1934 to the Internet in a vote expected on 26 February 2015.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Adoption of this notion would reclassify Internet service from one of information to one of the telecommunications and, according to Tom Wheeler, chairman of the FCC, ensure net neutrality.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] The FCC was expected to enforce net neutrality in its vote, according to *The New York Times*.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] On 26 February 2015, the FCC ruled in favor of net neutrality by adopting Title II (common carrier) of the Communications Act of 1934 and Section 706 in the Telecommunications Act of 1996 to the Internet.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] The FCC Chairman, Tom Wheeler, commented, "This is no more a plan to regulate the Internet than the First Amendment is a plan to regulate free speech.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] They both stand for the same concept." On 12 March 2015, the FCC released the specific details of the net neutrality rules.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] On 13 April 2015, the FCC published the final rule on its new "Net Neutrality" regulations.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] These rules went into effect on 12 June 2015.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Upon becoming FCC chairman in April 2017, Ajit Pai proposed an end to net neutrality, awaiting votes from the commission.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] On 21 November 2017, Pai announced that a vote will be held by FCC members on 14 December 2017 on whether to repeal the policy.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] On 11 June 2018, the repeal of the FCC's network neutrality rules took effect.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Since December 31, 2021, The Affordable Connectivity Program has given households in the U.S. at or below 200% of the Federal Poverty Guidelines or households that meet a number of other criteria an up to $30 per month discount toward Internet service, or up to $75 per month on certain tribal lands.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Access provider ISPs provide Internet access directly to end customers such as businesses and consumers, employing a range of technologies to connect users to their network.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Available technologies have ranged from computer modems with acoustic couplers to telephone lines, to television cable (CATV), Wi-Fi, and fiber optics.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] For users and small businesses, traditional options include copper wires to provide dial-up, DSL, typically asymmetric digital subscriber line (ADSL), cable modem or Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN) (typically basic rate interface).
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Using fiber-optics to end users is called Fiber To The Home or similar names.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Dedicated internet access (DIA) services for businesses can be delivered using PON networks.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Wireless access is another option, including cellular and satellite Internet access.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Access providers may have an MPLS (Multiprotocol label switching) or formerly a SONET backbone network, and have a ring or mesh network topology in their core network.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] The networks run by access providers can be considered wide area networks.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] ISPs can have access networks, aggregation networks/aggregation layers/distribution layers/edge routers/metro networks and a core network/backbone network; each subsequent network handles more traffic than the last.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Mobile service providers also have similar networks.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] A mailbox provider is an organization that provides services for hosting electronic mail domains with access to storage for mail boxes.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] It provides email servers to send, receive, accept, and store email for end users or other organizations.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Many mailbox providers are also access providers, but some are not (e.g., Gmail, Yahoo!
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] The definition given in RFC 6650 covers email hosting services, as well as the relevant departments of companies, universities, organizations, groups, and individuals that manage their mail servers themselves.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] The task is typically accomplished by implementing Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) and possibly providing access to messages through Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP), the Post Office Protocol, Webmail, or a proprietary protocol.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Internet hosting services provide email, web-hosting, or online storage services.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Other services include virtual server, cloud services, or physical server operation.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Just as their customers pay them for Internet access, ISPs themselves pay upstream ISPs for Internet access.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] An upstream ISP such as a tier 2 or tier 1 ISP usually has a larger network than the contracting ISP or is able to provide the contracting ISP with access to parts of the Internet the contracting ISP by itself has no access to.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] In the simplest case, a single connection is established to an upstream ISP and is used to transmit data to or from areas of the Internet beyond the home network; this mode of interconnection is often cascaded multiple times until reaching a tier 1 carrier.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] In reality, the situation is often more complex.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] ISPs with more than one point of presence (PoP) may have separate connections to an upstream ISP at multiple PoPs, or they may be customers of multiple upstream ISPs and may have connections to each one of them at one or more point of presence.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Transit ISPs provide large amounts of bandwidth for connecting hosting ISPs and access ISPs.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Border Gateway Protocol is used by routers to connect to other networks, which are identified by their autonomous system number.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Tier 2 ISPs depend on Tier 1 ISPs and often have their own networks, but must pay for transit or Internet access to Tier 1 ISPs, but may peer or send transit without paying, to other Tier 2 and/or some Tier 1 ISPs.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Tier 3 ISPs do not engage in peering and only purchase transit from Tier 2 and Tier 1 ISPs, and often specialize in offering Internet service to end customers such as businesses and individuals.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Some organizations act as their own ISPs and purchase transit directly from a Tier 1 ISP.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Transit ISPs may use OTN (Optical transport network) or SDH/SONET (Synchronous Digital Hierarchy/Synchronous Optical Networking) with a DWDM (Dense wavelength-division multiplexing) system for transmitting data through optical fiber over long distances such as across a city or between cities.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] For transmissions in a metro area such as a city and for large customers such as data centers, special pluggable modules in routers, conforming to standards such as CFP, QSFP-DD, OSFP, 400ZR or OpenZR+ may be used alongside DWDM and many vendors have proprietary offerings.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Long-haul networks transport data across longer distances than metro networks, such as through submarine cables, or connecting several metropolitan networks.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Optical line systems and packet optical transport systems can also be used for data transmission in metro areas, long haul connections and data center interconnect.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Ultra long haul transmission transports data over distances of over 1500 kilometers.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] ISPs connect to each other and to customers via data centers hosting meet-me rooms.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] A virtual ISP (VISP) is an operation that purchases services from another ISP, sometimes called a *wholesale ISP* in this context, which allow the VISP's customers to access the Internet using services and infrastructure owned and operated by the wholesale ISP.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] VISPs resemble mobile virtual network operators and competitive local exchange carriers for voice communications.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Free ISPs are Internet service providers that provide service free of charge.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Many free ISPs display advertisements while the user is connected; Like commercial television, in a sense, they are selling the user's attention to the advertiser.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Other free ISPs, sometimes called freenets, are run on a nonprofit basis, usually with volunteer staff.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] A wireless Internet service provider (WISP) is an Internet service provider with a network based on wireless networking.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] It is hypothesized that the vast divide between broadband connection in rural and urban areas is partially caused by a lack of competition between ISPs in rural areas, where there exists a market typically controlled by just one provider.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] A lack of competition problematically causes subscription rates to rise disproportionately with the quality of service in rural areas, causing broadband connection to be unaffordable for some, even when the infrastructure supports service in a given area.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] In contrast, consumers in urban areas typically benefit from lower rates and higher quality of broadband services, not only due to more advanced infrastructure but also the healthy economic competition caused by having several ISPs in a given area.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] How the difference in competition levels has potentially negatively affected the innovation and development of infrastructure in specific rural areas remains a question.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] The exploration and answers developed to the question could provide guidance for possible interventions and solutions meant to remedy the digital divide between rural and urban connectivity.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Altnets (portmanteau of "alternative network provider") are localized broadband networks, typically formed as an alternative to monopolistic Internet service providers within a region.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] ISPs requiring no upstream and having only customers or peers are called Tier 1 ISPs.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Network hardware, software and specifications, as well as the expertise of network management personnel, are important in ensuring that data follows the most efficient route, and upstream connections work reliably.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] A tradeoff between cost and efficiency is possible.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Tier 1 ISPs are also interconnected with a mesh network topology.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Internet Exchange Points (IXPs) are public locations where several networks are connected to each other.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Public peering is done at IXPs, while private peering can be done with direct links between networks.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] IXPs or peering exchanges may be located in data centers.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Furthermore, in some countries ISPs are subject to monitoring by intelligence agencies.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] In the U.S., a controversial National Security Agency program known as PRISM provides for broad monitoring of Internet users traffic and has raised concerns about potential violation of the privacy protections in the Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution.
[src:ovhcloud/internet-service-provider] Modern ISPs integrate a wide array of surveillance and packet sniffing equipment into their networks, which then feeds the data to law-enforcement/intelligence networks (such as DCSNet in the United States, or SORM in Russia) allowing monitoring of Internet traffic in real time.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] OVH was founded in November 1999 by Octave Klaba, with the help of three family members (Henry, Haline, and Miroslaw).
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In August 2023, it was announced OVHcloud was in exclusive negotiations for the acquisition of the Cologne-headquartered edge computing software company, gridscale GmbH.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] According to W3Techs, OVH is used by 3.1% of all websites.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In October 2016, OVH raised $250 million in order to raise further international expansion.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] This funding round valued OVH at over US$1 billion.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In the fiscal year of 2016, OVH reportedly had around $343 million in revenue.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In 2018 OVH announced its five-year plans to triple investment starting in 2021.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] Which represent between 4.6 and $8.1 billion U.S. dollars (4 to 7 billion euros).
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In October 2021, OVHcloud filed its IPO and is listed on the Euronext Paris, the Paris Stock Exchange as OVH.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In December 2021, OVHcloud became part of the Paris SBF120 index.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] As of 2021, OVH had 30 data centers in 19 countries hosting 300,000 servers.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] The company offers localized services such as customer service offices in many European countries, as well as in North America, Africa, and Singapore.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] As of 2017, OVH was known for its offering of email hosting service, considered one of the largest in the world, in addition to its general Internet hosting services.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] OVH uses in-house design and manufacturing, including custom-made servers (based on standard components) and a modular shipping container architecture.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In 2019, the Canadian data center (Beauharnois, Quebec) was considered a leading example of the OVH model.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In March 2025, OVHcloud US announced that it has expanded its network by introducing a Local Zone in Seattle, enhancing data processing speeds and connectivity for Pacific Northwest businesses.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] This addition aims to lower latency and support various cloud applications in the region.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] As of 2016, OVH was one of the sponsors for Let's Encrypt, a free TLS encryption service, and OVH's hardware supplier is Super Micro Computer Inc.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In March 2025, OVHcloud obtained the SecNumCloud 3.2 qualification for its highly secure cloud platform, Bare Metal Pod.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] Awarded by the French Cybersecurity Agency (ANSSI), this certification acknowledges the platform's adherence to stringent security standards.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] The qualification further supports OVHcloud's efforts in providing secure cloud solutions for public and private sector organizations, addressing strategic autonomy requirements and ensuring compliance for sensitive operations.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In March 2021, OVH suffered a large fire at its datacenter in Strasbourg, France.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] SBG2 had been built in 2016 with a capacity of 30,000 physical servers.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] SBG2 was declared a total loss, with early reports indicating damage to SBG1, and services across all four Strasbourg locations experiencing disruptions.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] The company's chairman, Octave Klaba, took to Twitter to confirm that all its staff were safe.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] All customer data and backups stored in SBG2 were lost.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] SBG1 was damaged partially while SBG4 remained intact, and SBG3 was intact but without power, though the servers at the latter sites were taken offline temporarily.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In September 2021, the company filed a report with the *Autorité des marchés financiers* documenting the estimated damage at about €105 million.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In 2023, OVH was ordered to pay €250,000 to two customers that had lost data, and more than 130 other customers are engaged in a class-action lawsuit against the company.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] In December 2010, French Gizmodo edition revealed that WikiLeaks selected OVH as its new hosting provider, following Amazon's refusal to host it.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] On December 3, the growing controversy prompted Eric Besson, France's Industry Minister, to inquire about legal ways to prohibit this hosting in France.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] On December 6, 2010, a judge ruled that there was no need for OVH to cease hosting WikiLeaks.
[src:ovhcloud/ovhcloud] The case was rejected on the grounds that such a case required an adversarial hearing.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] A **server** is a computer or software system that provides data, resources, or services to other computers called "clients" on a computer network.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] This architecture is called the client–server model.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Servers can provide various functionalities, often called "services", such as sharing data or resources among multiple clients or performing computations for a client.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] A single server can serve multiple clients, and a single client can use multiple servers.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] A client process may run on the same device or may connect over a network to a server on a different device.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Typical servers are database servers, file servers, mail servers, print servers, web servers, game servers, and application servers.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Client–server systems are most frequently implemented by (and often identified with) the request–response model: a client sends a request to the server, which performs some action and sends a response back to the client, typically with a result or acknowledgment.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Designating a computer as "server-class hardware" implies that it is specialized for running servers on it.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] This often implies that it is more powerful and reliable than standard personal computers.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] However, large computing clusters may also be composed of many relatively simple, replaceable server components.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The use of the word *server* in computing comes from queueing theory, where it dates to the mid 20th century, being notably used in Kendall (1953) (along with "service"), the paper that introduced Kendall's notation.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] In earlier papers, such as the Erlang (1909), more concrete terms such as "[telephone] operators" are used.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] In computing, "server" dates at least to RFC 5 (1969), one of the earliest documents describing ARPANET (the predecessor of Internet), and is contrasted with "user", distinguishing two types of host: "server-host" and "user-host".
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The use of "serving" also dates to early documents, such as RFC 4, contrasting "serving-host" with "using-host".
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The average utilization of a server in the early 2000s was 5 to 15%, but with the adoption of virtualization this figure started to increase the number of servers needed.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Strictly speaking, the term *server* refers to a computer program or process (running program).
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Through metonymy, it refers to a device used for (or a device dedicated to) running one or several server programs.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] On a network, such a device is called a *host*.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] In addition to *server*, the words *serve* and *service* (as verb and as noun respectively) are frequently used, though *servicer* and *servant* are not.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The word *service* (noun) may refer to the abstract form of functionality, e.g.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Alternatively, it may refer to a computer program that turns a computer into a server, e.g.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Originally used as "servers serve users" (and "users use servers"), in the sense of "obey", today one often says that "servers serve data", in the same sense as "give".
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] For instance, web servers "serve [up] web pages to users" or "service their requests".
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The server is part of the client–server model; in this model, a server serves data for clients.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The nature of communication between a client and server is request and response.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] This is in contrast with peer-to-peer model in which the relationship is on-demand reciprocation.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] In principle, any computerized process that can be used or called by another process (particularly remotely, particularly to share a resource) is a server, and the calling process or processes is a client.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Thus any general-purpose computer connected to a network can host servers.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] For example, if files on a device are shared by some process, that process is a file server.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Similarly, web server software can *run* on any capable computer, and so a laptop or a personal computer can host a web server.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] While request–response is the most common client-server design, there are others, such as the publish–subscribe pattern.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] In the publish-subscribe pattern, clients register with a pub-sub server, subscribing to specified types of messages; this initial registration may be done by request-response.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Thereafter, the pub-sub server forwards matching messages to the clients *without* any further requests: the server *pushes* messages to the client, rather than the client *pulling* messages from the server as in request-response.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The role of a server is to share data as well as to share resources and distribute work.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] A server computer can serve its own computer programs as well; depending on the scenario, this could be part of a *quid pro quo* transaction, or simply a technical possibility.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The following table shows several scenarios in which a server is used.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Almost the entire structure of the Internet is based upon a client–server model.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] High-level root nameservers, DNS, and routers direct the traffic on the internet.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] There are millions of servers connected to the Internet, running continuously throughout the world and virtually every action taken by an ordinary Internet user requires one or more interactions with one or more servers.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] There are exceptions that do not use dedicated servers; for example, peer-to-peer file sharing and some implementations of telephony (e.g. pre-Microsoft Skype).
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Hardware requirement for servers vary widely, depending on the server's purpose and its software.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Servers often are more powerful and expensive than the clients that connect to them.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The name server is used both for the hardware and software pieces.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] For the hardware servers, it is usually limited to mean the high-end machines although software servers can run on a variety of hardwares.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Since servers are usually accessed over a network, many run unattended without a computer monitor or input device, audio hardware and USB interfaces.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Many servers do not have a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] They are configured and managed remotely.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Remote management can be conducted via various methods including Microsoft Management Console (MMC), PowerShell, SSH and browser-based out-of-band management systems such as Dell's iDRAC or HP's iLo.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Large traditional single servers would need to be run for long periods without interruption.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Availability would have to be very high, making hardware reliability and durability extremely important.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Mission-critical enterprise servers would be very fault tolerant and use specialized hardware with low failure rates in order to maximize uptime.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Uninterruptible power supplies might be incorporated to guard against power failure.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Servers typically include hardware redundancy such as dual power supplies, RAID disk systems, and ECC memory, along with extensive pre-boot memory testing and verification.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Critical components might be hot swappable, allowing technicians to replace them on the running server without shutting it down, and to guard against overheating, servers might have more powerful fans or use water cooling.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] They will often be able to be configured, powered up and down, or rebooted remotely, using out-of-band management, typically based on IPMI.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Server casings are usually flat and wide, and designed to be rack-mounted, either on 19-inch racks or on Open Racks.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] These types of servers are often housed in dedicated data centers.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] These will normally have very stable power and Internet and increased security.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Noise is also less of a concern, but power consumption and heat output can be a serious issue.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Server rooms are equipped with air conditioning devices.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] A *server farm* or *server cluster* is a collection of computer servers maintained by an organization to supply server functionality far beyond the capability of a single device.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Modern data centers are now often built of very large clusters of much simpler servers, and there is a collaborative effort, Open Compute Project around this concept.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] A class of small specialist servers called network appliances are generally at the low end of the scale, often being smaller than common desktop computers.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] A mobile server has a portable form factor, e.g. a laptop.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] In contrast to large data centers or rack servers, the mobile server is designed for on-the-road or *ad hoc* deployment into emergency, disaster or temporary environments where traditional servers are not feasible due to their power requirements, size, and deployment time.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] The main beneficiaries of so-called "server on the go" technology include network managers, software or database developers, training centers, military personnel, law enforcement, forensics, emergency relief groups, and service organizations.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] To facilitate portability, features such as the keyboard, display, battery (uninterruptible power supply, to provide power redundancy in case of failure), and mouse are all integrated into the chassis.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] On the Internet, the dominant operating systems among servers are UNIX-like open-source distributions, such as those based on Linux and FreeBSD, with Windows Server also having a significant share.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Proprietary operating systems such as z/OS and macOS Server are also deployed, but in much smaller numbers.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Servers that run Linux are commonly used as Webservers or Databanks.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Windows Servers are used for Networks that are made out of Windows Clients.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] In practice, today many desktop and server operating systems share similar code bases, differing mostly in configuration.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] In 2024, data centers (servers, cooling, and other electrical infrastructure) consumed 415 terawatt-hours of electrical energy, and were responsible for roughly 1.5% of electrical energy consumption worldwide, and for 4.4% in the United States.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] One estimate is that total energy consumption for information and communications technology saves more than 5 times its carbon footprint in the rest of the economy by increasing efficiency.
[src:ovhcloud/server-computing] Concerns about data centers' environmental impact focus on their electricity demand and associated emissions, especially as AI workloads increase server and cooling requirements.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water cooling is commonly used for cooling automobile internal combustion engines and power stations.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water coolers utilising convective heat transfer are used inside some high-end personal computers to further lower the temperature of CPUs and other components compared to air cooling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Other uses include the cooling of lubricant oil in pumps; for cooling purposes in heat exchangers; for cooling buildings in HVAC and in chillers.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water is inexpensive, non-toxic, and available over most of the earth's surface.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Liquid cooling offers higher thermal conductivity than air cooling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water has unusually high specific heat capacity among commonly available liquids at room temperature and atmospheric pressure allowing efficient heat transfer over distance with low rates of mass transfer.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Cooling water may be recycled through a *recirculating* system or used in a single-pass *once-through cooling* (OTC) system.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water's high enthalpy of vaporization allows the option of efficient evaporative cooling to remove waste heat in cooling towers or cooling ponds.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Recirculating systems are *open* if they rely upon evaporative cooling or *closed* if heat removal is accomplished in heat exchangers, thus with negligible evaporative loss.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] A heat exchanger or condenser may separate *non-contact cooling water* from a fluid being cooled, or *contact cooling water* may directly impinge on items like saw blades where phase difference allows easy separation.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Environmental regulations emphasize the reduced concentrations of waste products in non-contact cooling water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water accelerates the corrosion of metal parts and is a favorable medium for biological growth.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Dissolved minerals in natural water supplies are concentrated by evaporation to leave deposits called scale.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Cooling water often requires the addition of chemicals to minimize corrosion and insulating deposits of scale and biofouling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water contains varying amounts of impurities from contact with the atmosphere, soil, and containers.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Being both an electrical conductor and a solvent for metal ions and oxygen, water can accelerate corrosion of machinery being cooled.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Corrosion reactions proceed more rapidly as temperature increases.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Preservation of machinery in the presence of hot water has been improved by addition of corrosion inhibitors including zinc, chromates and phosphates.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The first two have toxicity concerns; and the last has been associated with eutrophication.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Residual concentrations of biocides and corrosion inhibitors are of potential concern for OTC and blowdown from open recirculating cooling water systems.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] With the exception of machines with short design life, closed recirculating systems require periodic cooling-water treatment or replacement raising similar concern about ultimate disposal of cooling water containing chemicals used with environmental safety assumptions of a closed system.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Biofouling occurs because water is a favorable environment for many life forms.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Flow characteristics of recirculating cooling water systems encourage colonization by sessile organisms using the circulating supply of food, oxygen and nutrients.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Temperatures may become high enough to support thermophilic populations of organisms such as types of fungi.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Biofouling of heat exchange surfaces can reduce heat transfer rates of the cooling system, and biofouling of cooling towers can alter flow distribution to reduce evaporative cooling rates.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Biofouling may also create differential oxygen concentrations increasing corrosion rates.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] OTC and open recirculating systems are more susceptible to biofouling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Biofouling may be inhibited by temporary habitat modifications.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Temperature differences may discourage the establishment of thermophilic populations in intermittently operated facilities, and intentional short-term temperature spikes may periodically kill less tolerant populations.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Biocides have been commonly used to control biofouling where sustained facility operation is required.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Chlorine may be added in the form of hypochlorite to decrease biofouling in cooling water systems, but is later reduced to chloride to minimize the toxicity of blowdown or OTC water returned to natural aquatic environments.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Hypochlorite is increasingly destructive to wooden cooling towers as pH increases.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Chlorinated phenols have been used as biocides or leached from preserved wood in cooling towers.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Both hypochlorite and pentachlorophenol have reduced effectiveness at pH values greater than 8.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Non-oxidizing biocides may be more difficult to detoxify prior to release of blowdown or OTC water to natural aquatic environments.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] These increase salinity and total dissolved solids, and phosphorus compounds may provide the limiting essential nutrient for algal growth contributing to biofouling of the cooling system or to eutrophication of natural aquatic environments receiving blowdown or OTC water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Chromates reduce biofouling in addition to effective corrosion inhibition in the cooling water system, but residual toxicity in blowdown or OTC water has encouraged lower chromate concentrations and the use of less-flexible corrosion inhibitors.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Blowdown may also contain chromium leached from cooling towers constructed of wood preserved with chromated copper arsenate.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Total dissolved solids or TDS (sometimes called filterable residue) is reported as the mass of residue remaining when a measured volume of filtered water is evaporated.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Salinity indicates water density or conductivity changes caused by dissolved materials.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Probability of scale formation increases with increasing total dissolved solids.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Solids commonly associated with scale formation are calcium and magnesium both as carbonate and sulfate.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Corrosion rates initially increase with salinity in response to increasing electrical conductivity, but then decrease after reaching a peak as higher levels of salinity decrease dissolved oxygen levels.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Some groundwater contains very little oxygen when pumped from wells, but most natural water supplies include dissolved oxygen.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Increasing oxygen concentrations accelerate corrosion.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Dissolved oxygen approaches saturation levels in cooling towers.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] It is beneficial in blowdown or OTC water being returned to natural aquatic environments.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water ionizes into hydronium (H3O+) cations and hydroxide (OH−) anions.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The concentration of ionized hydrogen (as protonated water) in a cooling water system is reported as the pH level.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Low pH values increase the rate of corrosion; high pH values encourage scale formation.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Amphoterism is uncommon among metals used in water cooling systems, but aluminum corrosion rates increase with pH values above 9.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Galvanic corrosion may be severe in water systems with copper and aluminum components.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Acid can be added to cooling water systems to prevent scale formation if the pH decrease will offset increased salinity and dissolved solids.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Few other cooling applications approach the large volumes of water required to condense low-pressure steam at power stations.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Many facilities, particularly electric power plants, use millions of gallons of water per day for cooling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water cooling on this scale may alter natural water environments and create new environments.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Thermal pollution of rivers, estuaries and coastal waters is a consideration when siting such plants.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water returned to aquatic environments at temperatures higher than the ambient receiving water modifies aquatic habitat by increasing biochemical reaction rates and decreasing the oxygen saturation capacity of the habitat.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Temperature increases initially favor a population shift from species requiring the high-oxygen concentration of cold water to those enjoying the advantages of increased metabolic rates in warm water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Clean Water Act required the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) to issue regulations on industrial cooling water intake structures.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] EPA issued final regulations for new facilities in 2001 (amended 2003), and for existing facilities in 2014.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] As an alternative to OTC, industrial cooling towers may use recirculated river water, coastal water (seawater), or well water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Large mechanical induced-draft or forced-draft cooling towers in industrial plants continuously circulate cooling water through heat exchangers and other equipment where the water absorbs heat.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] That heat is then rejected to the atmosphere by the evaporation of some of the water in cooling towers where upflowing air contacts the downflowing water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The loss of evaporated water into the air exhausted to the atmosphere is replaced by "make-up" fresh river water or fresh cooling water, but the amount of water lost during evaporative cooling may affect the natural habitat for aquatic organisms.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The heated coolant mixture can be used to warm the air inside the car by means of the heater core.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Also, the water jacket around an engine is very effective at deadening mechanical noises, making the engine quieter.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] An open water cooling system makes use of evaporative cooling, lowering the temperature of the remaining (unevaporated) water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] This method was common in early internal combustion engines until scale buildup was observed from dissolved salts and minerals in the water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Modern open cooling systems continuously waste a fraction of recirculating water as blowdown to remove dissolved solids at concentrations low enough to prevent scale formation.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Some open systems use inexpensive tap water, but this requires higher blowdown rates than deionized or distilled water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Purified water systems still require blowdown to remove the accumulation of byproducts of chemical treatment to prevent corrosion and biofouling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water for cooling has a boiling point temperature of around 100 degrees C at atmospheric pressure.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Engines operating at higher temperatures may require a pressurized recycle loop to prevent overheating.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Modern automotive cooling systems often operate at 15 psi (103 kPa) to raise the boiling-point of the recycling water coolant and reduce evaporative losses.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The use of water cooling carries the risk of damage from freezing.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Automotive and many other engine cooling applications require the use of a water and antifreeze mixture to lower the freezing point to a temperature unlikely to be experienced.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Antifreeze also inhibits corrosion from dissimilar metals and can increase the boiling point, allowing a wider range of water cooling temperatures.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Its distinctive odor also alerts operators to cooling system leaks and problems that would go unnoticed in a water-only cooling system.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Other less common chemical additives are products to reduce surface tension.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] These additives are meant to increase the efficiency of automotive cooling systems.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Such products are used to enhance the cooling of underperforming or undersized cooling systems or in racing where the weight of a larger cooling system could be a disadvantage.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Since approximately 1930 it is common to use water cooling for tubes of powerful transmitters.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] As these devices use high operation voltages (around 10 kV), the use of deionized water is required and it has to be carefully controlled.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Modern solid-state transmitters can be built so that even high-power transmitters do not require water cooling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water cooling is however also sometimes used for thyristors of HVDC valves, for which the use of deionized water is required.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Liquid cooling techniques are increasingly being used for the thermal management of electronic components.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] This type of cooling is a solution to ensure the optimisation of energy efficiency while simultaneously minimising noise and space requirements.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Especially useful in supercomputers or Data Centers because maintenance of the racks is quick and easy.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] After disassembly of the rack, advanced-technology quick-release couplings eliminate spillage for the safety of operators and protect the integrity of fluids (no impurities in the circuits).
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] These couplings are also capable of being locked (Panel mounted?) to allow blind connection in difficult-to-access areas.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water cooling often adds complexity and cost in comparison to air cooling design by requiring a pump, tubing or piping to transport the water, and a radiator, often with fans, to reject the heat to the atmosphere.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Depending on the application, water cooling may create an additional element of risk where leakage from the water coolant recycle loop can corrode or short-circuit sensitive electronic components.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The primary advantage of water cooling for cooling CPU cores in computing equipment is transporting heat away from the source to a secondary cooling surface to allow for large, more optimally designed radiators rather than small, relatively inefficient fins mounted directly on the heat source.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Cooling hot computer components with various fluids has been in use since at least the Cray-2 in 1982, which used Fluorinert.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Through the 1990s, water cooling for home PCs slowly gained recognition among enthusiasts, but it became noticeably more prevalent after the introduction of the first Gigahertz-clocked processors in the early 2000s.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] As of 2018, there are dozens of manufacturers of water cooling components and kits, and many computer manufacturers include preinstalled water cooling solutions for their high-performance systems.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water cooling can be used for many computer components, but usually it is used for the CPU and GPUs.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water cooling typically uses a water block, a water pump, and a water-to-air heat exchanger.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] By transferring device heat to a separate larger heat exchanger using larger, lower-speed fans, water cooling can allow quieter operation, improved processor speeds (overclocking), or a balance of both.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Less commonly, Northbridges, Southbridges, hard disk drives, memory, voltage regulator modules (VRMs), and even power supplies can be water-cooled.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Internal radiator size may vary: from 40 mm dual fan (80 mm) to 140 quad fan (560 mm) and thickness from 30 mm to 80 mm.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Radiator fans may be mounted on one or both sides.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] External radiators can be much larger than their internal counterparts as they do not need to fit in the confines of a computer case.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] High-end cases may have two rubber grommeted ports in the back for the inlet and outlet hoses, which allow external radiators to be placed far away from the PC.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] A *T-Line* is used to remove trapped air bubbles from the circulating water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] It is made with a t-connector and a capped-off length of tubing.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The tube n acts as a mini-reservoir and allows air bubbles to travel into it as they are caught into the "tee" connector, and ultimately removed from the system by bleeding.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The capped line may be capped with a fill-port fitting to allow the release of trapped gas and the addition of liquid.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water coolers for desktop computers were, until the end of the 1990s, homemade.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] More recently a growing number of companies are manufacturing water-cooling components compact enough to fit inside a computer case.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] This, and the trend to CPUs of higher power dissipation, has greatly increased the popularity of water cooling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Dedicated overclockers have occasionally used vapor-compression refrigeration or thermoelectric coolers in place of more common standard heat exchangers.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The downside of phase-change or thermoelectric cooling is that it uses much more electricity, and antifreeze must be added due to the low temperature.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Additionally, insulation, usually in the form of lagging around water pipes and neoprene pads around the components to be cooled, must be used in order to prevent damage caused by condensation of water vapour from the air on chilled surfaces.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Common places from which to obtain the required phase transition systems are a household dehumidifier or air conditioner.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Because the only sub-ambient temperature zone now is at the interface with the heat-generating component itself, insulation is required only in that localized area.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The disadvantage of such a system is higher power dissipation.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] To avoid damage from condensation around the Peltier junction, a proper installation requires it to be "potted" with silicone epoxy.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] The epoxy is applied around the edges of the device, preventing air from entering or leaving the interior.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Apple's Power Mac G5 was the first mainstream desktop computer to have water cooling as standard (although only on its fastest models).
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Dell followed suit by shipping their XPS computers with liquid cooling, using thermoelectric cooling to help cool the liquid.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Currently, Dell's only computers to offer liquid cooling are their Alienware desktops.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Asus are the first and only mainstream brand to have put water-cooled laptops into mass production.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Those laptops have a built-in air/water hybrid cooling system and can be docked to an external liquid cooling radiator for additional cooling and electrical power.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water is an ideal cooling medium for vessels as they are constantly surrounded by water that generally remains at a low temperature throughout the year.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Systems operating with seawater need to be manufactured from cupronickel, bronze, titanium or similarly corrosion-resistant materials.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water containing sediment may require velocity restrictions through piping to avoid erosion at high velocity or blockage by settling at low velocity.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Plant transpiration and animal perspiration use evaporative cooling to prevent high temperatures from causing unsustainable metabolic rates.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Machine guns used in fixed defensive positions sometimes use water cooling to extend barrel life through periods of rapid fire, but the weight of the water and pumping system significantly reduces the portability of water-cooled firearms.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Water-cooled machine guns were extensively used by both sides during World War I; however, by the end of the war lighter weapons that rivaled the firepower, effectiveness and reliability of water-cooled models began to appear on the battlefield.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Thus water-cooled weapons have played a far lesser role in subsequent conflicts.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] A hospital in Sweden relies on snow-cooling from melt-water to cool its data centers, medical equipment, and maintain a comfortable ambient temperature.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Some nuclear reactors use heavy water as coolant.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Heavy water is employed in nuclear reactors because it is a weaker neutron absorber.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] This allows for the use of less-enriched fuel.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] For the main cooling system, normal water is preferably employed through the use of a heat exchanger, as heavy water is much more expensive.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Reactors that use other materials for moderation (graphite) may also use normal water for cooling.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] High-grade industrial water (produced by reverse osmosis or distillation) and potable water are sometimes used in industrial plants requiring high-purity cooling water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] Production of these high-purity waters creates waste byproduct brines containing the concentrated impurities from the source water.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] In 2018, researchers from the University of Colorado Boulder and University of Wyoming invented a radiative cooling metamaterial known as "RadiCold", which has been developed since 2017.
[src:ovhcloud/watercooling] This metamaterial aids in cooling of water and increasing the efficiency of power generation, in which it would cool the underneath objects, by reflecting away the sun's rays while at the same time allowing the surface to discharge its heat as infrared thermal radiation.
